ct of the 1982 mental disease epidemiological survey\", \"explanation\": \"The 1982 mental disease epidemiological survey was the first nationwide study in China to use unified international screening tools and diagnostic standards. This survey provided comprehensive data on the prevalence and distribution of mental disorders across 12 regions, offering valuable insights for the development of CCMD-2. The findings from this survey highlighted the need for standardized diagnostic criteria and informed the subsequent revisions of the CCMD framework [Data: Entities (357); Relationships (432)].\" }, { \"summary\": \"Contribution of the Chinese Neuropsychiatric Society\", \"explanation\": \"The Chinese Neuropsychiatric Society played a crucial role in the development and approval of CCMD-2. The society organized the expanded meeting in Xi'an in 1989, which resulted in the official approval of CCMD-2. This meeting brought together key stakeholders in the field of psychiatry, ensuring that the diagnostic standards were both scientifically valid and widely accepted. The society's involvement underscores the importance of collaborative efforts in the advancement of mental health diagnostics [Data: Entities (449); Relationships (531)].\" }, { \"summary\": \"Integration of international diagnostic frameworks\", \"explanation\": \"The development of CCMD-2 was influenced by international diagnostic frameworks, such as the DSM-III, which introduced significant changes in the classification of mental disorders. The integration of these international standards into the Chinese context allowed for a more comprehensive and globally relevant diagnostic framework. This cross-cultural exchange of knowledge has been instrumental in advancing the field of psychiatry in China [Data: Entities (299); Relationships (368)].\" }, { \"summary\": \"Role of academic conferences in CCMD development\", \"explanation\": \"Academic conferences held in various Chinese cities, including Suzhou, Huangshan, and Guiyang, played a significant role in the development of CCMD-1. These conferences focused on specific mental disorders, such as schizophrenia, manic-depressive psychosis, and neurosis, and contributed to the development of clinical diagnostic standards. The insights gained from these conferences informed the creation of CCMD-1 and laid the groundwork for subsequent editions of the CCMD [Data: Entities (439, 440, 441); Relationships (525, 526, 527)].\" } ] }", "refusal": null, "role": "assistant", "annotations": null, "audio": null, "function_call": null, "tool_calls": null}}], "created": 1744255985, "model": "deepseek-v3", "object": "chat.completion", "service_tier": null, "system_fingerprint": null, "usage": {"completion_tokens": 1177, "prompt_tokens": 5104, "total_tokens": 6281, "completion_tokens_details": null, "prompt_tokens_details": null}}, "input": {"messages": [{"content": "\nYou are an AI assistant that helps a human analyst to perform general information discovery. Information discovery is the process of identifying and assessing relevant information associated with certain entities (e.g., organizations and individuals) within a network.\n\n# Goal\nWrite a comprehensive report of a community, given a list of entities that belong to the community as well as their relationships and optional associated claims. The report will be used to inform decision-makers about information associated with the community and their potential impact. The content of this report includes an overview of the community's key entities, their legal compliance, technical capabilities, reputation, and noteworthy claims.\n\n# Report Structure\n\nThe report should include the following sections:\n\n- TITLE: community's name that represents its key entities - title should be short but specific. When possible, include representative named entities in the title.\n- SUMMARY: An executive summary of the community's overall structure, how its entities are related to each other, and 